"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046172","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-01-29","<p>There have been no unauthorised incursions by any foreign military aircraft into sovereign air space around the UK, which projects 12 miles off shore or to mutually agreed mid-points between adjacent nations over narrow straits such as the Straits of Dover. The UK civil air traffic region and the NATO Air Policing Area, which the UK has responsibility for monitoring, include large areas of international airspace through which foreign military traffic may legally transit.</p><p>The airspace around and approaching the UK is permanently monitored and RAF Typhoon Quick Reaction Alert aircraft stand ready to scramble and intercept aircraft approaching the UK if required.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-01-29T13:52:42.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046172/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046172/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-01-22","Air Space: Defence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps the Government is taking to reduce the number of incursions into British airspace by foreign military aircraft.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","211188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046174","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-28","<p>NHS England Liaison and Diversion services are able to assess vulnerable individuals, including former service personnel at first point of contact with the Criminal Justice System, for example at police stations and courts across England. Individuals may be diverted away from the Criminal Justice System, or into appropriate community orders.</p><p> </p><p>Project Nova in partnership with NHS Liaison &amp; Diversion services across four regions, are able to offer former service personnel support to address the underlying issues that lead to re-offending.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice understands the unique nature of those who served in the Armed Forces and those prisoners who declare a military background are able to access a range of specialist support, including from military charities who deliver services in prisons and in the community.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-01-28T13:19:40.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046174/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046174/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-22","Prisoners: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to reduce the number of armed forces veterans in prison.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","211189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046175","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-30","<p>The Foreign Secretary and Lord Ahmad have had a number of recent engagements with religious leaders, interested organisations and parliamentarians on the question of the persecution of Christians around the world, including in the Middle East and North Africa. The Foreign Secretary has requested that the Bishop of Truro leads a review of British Government support for persecuted Christians. I regularly raise the issues being faced by Christians and other religious minorities during my meetings with governments in the Middle East and North Africa. The UK remains committed to supporting the fundamental human right of all persons to practice, change or share their faith or belief without discrimination or violent opposition.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2019-01-30T15:22:12.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046175/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046175/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","North Africa: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has received on the persecution of Christians in North Africa; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","211190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046176","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-01-29","<p>The programme is on schedule to complete the relocation of its major units from Germany in 2019. Since 2010, over 16,000 troops (82% of the 2010 footprint in Germany) have relocated to the UK. This includes the building of 1,500 new military houses and 4,500 single bed spaces.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2019-01-29T13:30:37.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046176/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046176/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-01-22","Army: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress has been made on the re-basing of the British Army from Germany to the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","211191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046177","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-01-29","<p>Operation CABRIT is not currently a medal-earning operation. All operations change over time and so the Ministry of Defence reviews medallic recognition for all operations on a periodic basis. Operation CABRIT will be subject to this review process in due course.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-01-29T13:33:49.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046177/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046177/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-01-22","Baltic States and Poland: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of awarding the General Service Medal to British forces personnel who are serving on Operation Cabrit.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","211192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046178","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-30","<p>The UK remains concerned by continued issues related to religious freedom in Iraq but welcomes signs that Iraq's new leadership is actively promoting respect for religious minorities. For example, the Vatican Secretary of State made an official visit to Iraq in December, and the Iraqi Prime Minister's new Cabinet declared Christmas Day an official holiday for all Iraqis, not just Christians.</p><p>The UK is committed to promoting and protecting the right to freedom of religion or belief across Iraq. We regularly underline this to Iraqi political leaders, emphasising that this right is critical to building an inclusive, stable and tolerant country. Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon reinforced this message with the new Iraqi Foreign Minister Al-Hakim in December 2018. As part of our efforts, we are also funding a project to pilot a new curriculum on freedom of religion or belief in secondary schools in Iraq.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2019-01-30T16:50:31.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046178/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046178/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Iraq: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the level of religious freedom in Iraq; and what steps the Government is taking to promote and protect the right to freedom of religion or belief in that country.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","211193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046292","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-06","<p>We are conducting a Joint Trade and Investment Review with China, which is an important part of significantly deepening our trade and investment partnership. We have made good progress and aim to agree recommendations in 2019. The UK-India Joint Trade Review was concluded in January 2018 and the UK-Brazil Joint Trade Review was concluded in March 2018. The UK is committed to working collaboratively with both India and Brazil to deepen the bilateral trade relationship, both before and after the UK leaves the EU. We have made good progress - for example through removing barriers affecting UK businesses.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2019-02-06T13:27:26.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046292/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046292/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046292/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-22","Overseas Trade: Reviews","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many joint trade reviews they have undertaken with other countries in the last 12 months; and with which countries such reviews were undertaken.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL13003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046293","Department for International Trade","false","2019-01-29","<p>The UK cannot negotiate and conclude trade agreements while we are still a member of the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Joint Trade Reviews are a collaborative in-depth analysis into the mutual trading relationship between the UK and our partners to look for areas we can improve our bilateral trading relationships.   We will aim through these discussions to put in place various mechanisms to improve trading relations, remove barriers affecting UK businesses and bring benefits to UK consumers after we leave the EU.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2019-01-29T15:59:13.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046293/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046293/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046293/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-22","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many joint trade reviews conducted with other countries in the last 12 months have resulted in the UK reaching agreement on free trade arrangements to come into force after the UK leaves the EU; and with which countries those free trade agreements have been concluded.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL13004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046294","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-05","<p>The UK and Swiss governments have agreed the text of a trade agreement which the Government expects to sign shortly.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside the Withdrawal Agreement, the EU agreed to notify its treaty partners that the UK is treated as a Member State for the purposes of EU international agreements during the Implementation Period (IP). This includes trade agreements.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will be updating businesses and Parliament on the progress of this programme of work shortly.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2019-02-05T14:34:51.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046294/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046294/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-22","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have agreed free trade agreements for when the UK leaves the EU with (1) Norway, (2) Switzerland, (3) South Korea, and (4) Turkey; and if not, when they expect to do so.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL13005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046296","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-05","<p>Discussions with all partner countries have demonstrated a commitment to finding a pragmatic way to ensure continuity of our existing international agreements. Alongside the Withdrawal Agreement, the EU agreed to notify its treaty partners that the UK is treated as a Member State for the purposes of EU international agreements during the Implementation Period (IP). This includes trade agreements.</p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to prepare for all eventualities, including a ‘no deal’ Brexit scenario, in the event of which we will seek to bring into force bilateral agreements from exit day (29 March 2019) or as soon as possible thereafter. We are making good progress and have signed agreements with Chile, the Faroe Islands, and Eastern and Southern African Economic Partnership Agreement states, with others soon to follow, such as Switzerland, which the Government expects to sign shortly. We have also signed Mutual Recognition Agreements with Australia and New Zealand. When we reach agreement with other countries will depend on the progress of ongoing discussions, taking into account: their assessment of the possibility of a no deal; their own political or parliamentary situation; resource constraints; and other factors. The Government will continue to inform Parliament and the public when agreements are signed.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2019-02-05T17:45:02.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046296/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046296/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-22","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many of the current EU free trade agreements they have agreed to replicate with the countries concerned so that the UK will be able to continue to trade with those countries on existing terms after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL13006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046297","Department for Education","false","2019-02-01","<p>​There is no place for extremism in our society and extremist views should be exposed and challenged.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education has not engaged with any institutions, including SOAS University of London, in relation to the Henry Jackson Society report.</p><p> </p><p>The government believes that free speech should been encouraged, provided that it is within the law as it encourages debate and understanding. Challenging extremist speakers and events is an important part of tackling extremist narratives. However, this does not mean closing down lawful speech, but rather ensuring the right steps are taken to counter extremist narratives and make sure that those who wish to spread hatred do not go unchallenged.</p><p> </p><p>The Prevent duty requires higher education institutions to ensure they have mitigated the risk of extremist speakers spreading harmful narratives before an event can go ahead.</p><p> </p><p>​The Equality and Human Rights Commission is developing new guidance on freedom of speech in higher education, which will be published shortly.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2019-02-01T14:53:40.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046297/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046297/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-22","School of Oriental and African Studies: Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the finding of the report by the Henry Jackson Society Extreme Speakers and Events: In the 2017–18 Academic Year, published on 21 January, that SOAS University of London has hosted 70 events that were addressed by extremist speakers; whether they have discussed that report with SOAS; if so, what was the outcome of any such discussions; and what steps they intend to take in response.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL13007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046298","Home Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>The basis of a person’s asylum claim is recorded on their individual Home Office file, but not in a way that can be easily aggregated, so we cannot provide figures on how many claims are brought by particular persecuted minorities, or the nature of claims brought by those attempting to travel to the UK in small vessels.</p><p>As such, this information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost because it would require a manual search through individual records.</p><p>We keep all policy under regular review.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL13009","2019-02-05T15:17:50.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046298/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046298/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-01-22","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 21 January (HL12624) that “the Home Office does not electronically record the grounds on which an individual claims asylum” and that they cannot identify the origins of persecuted minorities, whether they intend to (1) review that policy, and (2) collect such data in the future.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL13008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046299","Home Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>The basis of a person’s asylum claim is recorded on their individual Home Office file, but not in a way that can be easily aggregated, so we cannot provide figures on how many claims are brought by particular persecuted minorities, or the nature of claims brought by those attempting to travel to the UK in small vessels.</p><p>As such, this information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost because it would require a manual search through individual records.</p><p>We keep all policy under regular review.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL13008","2019-02-05T15:17:50.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046299/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046299/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-01-22","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 21 January (HL12624) that “the Home Office does not electronically record the grounds on which an individual claims asylum”, whether they record that information by other means; if so, whether data are available for those that attempted to travel to the UK on small vessels in 2018; and if so, whether they will publish any such data.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL13009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046301","Department for International Development","false","2019-02-05","<p>The exact number of Christians in Iraq is difficult to confirm, as Iraq has not held a nationwide census in many years. The UK remains concerned by the decreasing number of Christians and we are firmly committed to protecting all ethnic and religious minorities in Iraq and the region. Minister Burt met with the Archbishop of Erbil during his recent trip to Iraq, and UK Embassy staff regularly meet with representatives of Christian and other minority communities to discuss their situation. We continue to raise the needs of these communities with the Government of Iraq. For example, Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon reinforced the need to protect ethnic and religious minority communities with Iraqi Foreign Minister Al-Hakim in December 2018.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2019-02-05T17:34:49.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046301/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046301/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-01-22","Iraq: Christianity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 21 January (HL12614), what assessment they have made of the comments of Chaldean Archbishop Habib Nafali of Basra that the Christian population of Iraq has reduced from around 1.5 million in 2003 to 250,000 in 2018.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL13010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046302","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-02-04","<p>Delivering a deal with the EU remains the best way to guarantee no hard border. The UK Government is clear that, in the event of no deal, we will do everything in our power to prevent a return to a hard border.</p><p>The Government recognises that in a no deal scenario it would need to engage constructively with Ireland and the Commission to find the best way to avoid a hard border.</p><p>In all scenarios the UK will be unwavering in its commitment to the Belfast Agreement and the people of Northern Ireland.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2019-02-04T15:19:23.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046302/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046302/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-01-22","Borders: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans, if any, they have to erect a hard border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland in the event of a no-deal Brexit; and what costs have been incurred so far in preparation for such an outcome.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL13011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046303","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-04","<p>There are conflicting media reports on claims of genetic modification in China. We shall continue to monitor the situation. We have had no discussion with the Chinese Government regarding the ethical issues and risks associated with the gene-edited babies born in China. The procedure alleged to have been carried out by Prof He Jiankui in China would be illegal in the UK. It would be an offence under the 1990 Human Fertilisation &amp; Embryology Act (1990 Act), punishable, on conviction, by a prison term of up to 10 years, a fine or both.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-04T17:09:43.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046303/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046303/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","China: Genetic Engineering","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations, if any, they have made to the government of China about reports that babies have been born in China with edited genes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Berridge",,"Baroness Berridge","HL13012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046304","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-30","<p>There are conflicting media reports on claims of genetic modification in China. We will continue to monitor the situation. We have had no discussion with the Chinese Government or World Health Organization regarding the ethical issues and risks associated with the gene-edited babies born in China. The procedure alleged to have been carried out by Prof He Jiankui in China would be illegal in the United Kingdom. It would be an offence under the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 1990, punishable, on conviction, by a prison term of up to 10 years, a fine or both.</p>",,"Baroness Manzoor",,"2019-01-30T17:45:44.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046304/answer","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046304/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-22","China: Genetic Engineering","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with the World Health Organisation about the ethical issues and potential long-term risks associated with gene-edited babies born in China.","false","Biography information for Baroness Berridge",,"Baroness Berridge","HL13013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046305","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-02-04","<p>The Government values the work of our world-renowned judiciary. We are carefully considering all the recommendations and observations made by the SSRB’s major review, which include those relating to pay and working conditions</p><p>An additional £1 billion investment through the HMCTS Reform programme has already started to improve our courts. Introducing digital services and more efficient ways of working through the programme will free up judges from routine tasks so they can focus on the most contentious issues.</p><p>In reflection of concerns raised by the judiciary about the courts and tribunals estate, the Government has invested an additional £15 million this year to carry out much needed security and maintenance work to improve the conditions of courts across England and Wales. This work is currently underway.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2019-02-04T11:45:22.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046305/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046305/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-22","Judiciary: Working Conditions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the report to the Senior Salaries Review Body The attractiveness of judicial appointments in the United Kingdom, published in January 2018, what plans they have to improve working conditions for judges.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL13014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046306","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-28","<p>Activity to address high staff turnover, which runs the risk of losing corporate memory, includes: using career pathways and frameworks to support the development of expertise for roles and professions; pay related solutions for both the Senior Civil Service and delegated grades, including enabling departments to give capability based pay rewards at the delegated grades; and, encouraging the use of Pivotal Role Allowances.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2019-01-28T14:48:02.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046306/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046306/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-01-22","Government Departments: Labour Turnover","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to reduce staff turnover in Government departments.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL13015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046307","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-05","<p>The Government is committed to working to provide continuity across all our existing trade agreements. In a no-deal scenario we will work to achieve this for as many agreements as possible, just as we are now.</p><p> </p><p>We are making good progress and have signed agreements with Chile, the Faroe Islands, and Eastern and Southern African Economic Partnership Agreement states with others soon to follow, such as Switzerland, which the Government expects to sign shortly. We have also signed Mutual Recognition Agreements with Australia and New Zealand. When we reach agreement with other countries will depend on the progress of ongoing discussions, taking into account: their assessment of the possibility of a no deal; their own political or parliamentary situation; resource constraints; and other factors. The Government will continue to inform Parliament and the public when agreements are signed.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2019-02-05T17:49:36.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046307/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046307/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-22","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether their plan to replicate 40 existing EU free trade agreements before the UK leaves the EU is on schedule.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL13016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046308","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-05","<p>Each general practice is required to provide services to meet the reasonable needs of their registered population. There is no recommendation for how many patients a general practitioner (GP) should have, as the demand each patient places on their GP is different and can be affected by various factors, including rurality and patient demographics. The workforce required for each practice to meet patient needs also includes a range of health professionals in addition to GPs themselves, and the best skill mix is for practices to determine.</p><p>NHS England and Health Education England (HEE) are working together with the profession to increase the GP workforce in England. This includes measures to boost recruitment, address the reasons why GPs are leaving the profession, and encourage GPs to return to practice.</p><p>Last year, Health Education England recruited the highest number of GP trainees ever and the Targeted Enhanced Recruitment Scheme (TERs) is attracting GP trainees to parts of the country where there have been consistent shortages of GP trainees. Over 500 trainees entered the TERs scheme in 2016-2018 and a further 276 are available in 2019.</p><p>NHS England has committed to further expanding community based multi-disciplinary teams and will provide funding for around 20,000 other staff in primary care networks by 2023/24. This builds on the extra 3,700 non-GP clinical staff already working in general practice, compared to 2015 and will mean bigger teams of staff, providing a wider range of care options for patients and freeing up more time for GPs to focus on those with more complex needs.</p><p>The recently published NHS Long Term Plan made a clear commitment to the future of general practice, with primary and community care set to receive at least £4.5 billion more in real terms a year by 2023/24 – meaning their funding will grow faster than the rising National Health Service budget. Since the launch of the Long Term Plan, NHS England and the British Medical Association’s General Practitioners Committee have agreed a five-year GP (General Medical Services) contract framework from 2019/20. The new contract framework will be essential to deliver the ambitions set out in the NHS Long Term Plan through strong general practice services.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-02-05T12:46:01.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046308/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046308/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-22","General Practitioners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to reduce the variation across Clinical Commissioning Groups in England in the ratio between GPs and their patients.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL13017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046309","Department for Education","false","2019-02-01","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p>Data is collected by the department on assessments for education, health and care (EHC) plans that are completed within their 20-week target. This is published, at local authority level, in table 8 of the “Statements of special educational needs and EHC plans: England 2018” publication attached and available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2018</a>.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2019-02-01T14:01:51.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046309/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046309/answer","HL13018_New_EHC_plans_issued_within_20_weeks_by_local_authority.xls","HL13018_New_EHC_plans_issued_within_20_weeks_by_lo","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046309/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-22","Special Educational Needs: Greater Manchester","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the current waiting time for children with special educational needs to have education, health and care plans (1) processed, and (2) implemented, in each of the ten districts of Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL13018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046310","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>​The UK shares common values with Europe, and faces common threats. We will continue to cooperate across a wide range of issues once we have left the EU and will remain members of the Council of Europe, the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe, and NATO, each of which have an important part to play in supporting co-operation in Europe and beyond. We will continue to work with our allies and partners to ensure that these organisations modernise and adapt to evolving challenges.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-05T12:32:56.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046310/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046310/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Europe: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they are taking steps to achieve a better definition and distribution of responsibility for issues affecting Europe between (1) the Council of Europe, (2) the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe, (3) NATO, and (4) the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL13019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046311","Department for Transport","false","2019-01-29","<p>Her Majesty’s Coastguard is actively considering drone technology that could be used to enhance search and rescue efficiency across the UK, save more lives and reduce risk to personnel. This includes working with search and rescue partners and industry, to explore and trial the feasibility of using drones in real-life scenarios, which will improve situational awareness and decision making for search and rescue authorities.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2019-01-29T15:28:00.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046311/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046311/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-01-22","Rescue Services: Unmanned Air Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration they are giving to the use of drones for air-sea rescue purposes in the English Channel.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL13020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046313","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-02-04","<p>Refugees granted limited or indefinite leave to remain will satisfy the legal right to reside requirement and are exempt from the assessment of factual habitual residence.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2019-02-04T11:59:37.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046313/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046313/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-22","Habitual Residence Test: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether refugees are required to undertake the (1) habitual residence, and (2) right to reside parts of the habitual residence test.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL13021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046314","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-02-05","<p>Refugees who accept assistance through the Post Grant Appointment Service will be assessed to ascertain whether they have complex needs and so require additional support to ensure that their customer journey is equal in quality and outcome to that of someone who does not have complex needs.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2019-02-05T15:14:39.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046314/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046314/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-22","Social Security Benefits: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will publish guidance that sets out the additional help that is available through the Department for Work and Pensions' vulnerable person’s pathway for refugees who accept assistance through the Post Grant Appointment Service.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL13022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046315","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-02-04","<p>Those who do not have a bank account, including refugees, can have their Universal Credit award paid through a Post Office Card Account, or alternatively payments can be made into someone else’s bank account. Payments can also be made using the Government Payment Exception Service.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2019-02-04T12:00:03.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046315/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046315/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-22","Universal Credit: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the recommendation in the report by the British Red Cross Still an Ordeal: the move on period for refugees, published on 6 December 2018, to allow refugees who do not have a bank account to use the existing asylum support payment (ASPEN) card for their first Universal Credit payment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL13023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046316","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-02-04","<p>We have conducted an informal evaluation of the Post Grant Appointment Service, which includes looking at refugees claiming Universal Credit as well as legacy benefits and intend to write to the Work and Pensions Select Committee detailing our findings. Our response to the Committee will be published.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2019-02-04T12:06:12.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046316/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046316/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-22","Universal Credit: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to publish an evaluation of the impact of the Post Grant Appointment Service on the transition of refugees to Universal Credit; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL13024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046317","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-05","<p>Over the last year, and at no cost, the Department has consulted with a range of experts in tobacco control, none of whom have any connections with the tobacco industry. The Department has also consulted with the Health Ministries of other countries that have world leading tobacco control programmes.</p><p>The external advice provided to the Department has been part of the formulation of Government policy and therefore, we have no plans to publish the advice at this current time.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-02-05T12:42:51.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046317/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046317/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046317/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-22","Tobacco: Packaging","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have commissioned advice from any company, organisation or individual about the proposed changes to tobacco product packaging in the event of a no-deal Brexit; if so, which company, organisation or individual they commissioned such advice from; what was the cost of any such advice; and whether they will place a copy of any such advice in the Library of the House.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL13025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046318","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-02-04","<p>Alongside the Confidence &amp; Supply Agreement, the UK Government has committed to providing £1 billion of additional funding to Northern Ireland departments. A total of £430 million from the financial annex to the Confidence and Supply Agreement has been allocated to the Northern Ireland block grant. The remaining £570 million has not yet been allocated and would be subject to Parliament’s approval through the usual Estimates process.</p><p> </p><p>Further details on funding allocations are set out in the financial annex to the Confidence and Supply Agreement at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/conservative-and-dup-agreement-and-uk-government-financial-support-for-northern-ireland/uk-government-financial-support-for-northern-ireland" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/conservative-and-dup-agreement-and-uk-government-financial-support-for-northern-ireland/uk-government-financial-support-for-northern-ireland </a></p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-02-04T11:59:15.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046318/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046318/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-01-22","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much of the additional financial support allocated to Northern Ireland as a direct result of the confidence and supply agreement with the Democratic Unionist Party (1) has been spent, and (2) remains to be spent.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL13026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046319","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-02-05","<p>The UK Government is clear that, in the event of no deal, we will do everything in our power to prevent a return to a hard border. In such a scenario, we must continue to respect our unique relationship with Ireland, with whom we share a land border and who are co-signatories of the Belfast Agreement.</p><p>We recognise that we would need to take forward discussions with the Irish government and the European Commission in the event of a no deal on the best way to achieve this.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2019-02-05T16:54:43.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046319/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046319/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-01-22","Borders: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions have been held with the EU about the erection of physical infrastructure on the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland in the event of a no-deal Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL13027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046320","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>The Minister for Africa, Minister Baldwin, spoke to Zimbabwe's Foreign Minister on 29 January. The Minister also summoned the Zimbabwean Ambassador on 17 January to express our concern at the ongoing situation in Zimbabwe. Minister Baldwin urged Zimbabwe to stop disproportionate use of force by the security forces and investigate any cases of alleged human rights abuses. On 21 January the Foreign Secretary, in a public message to President Mnangagwa, urged him not to turn back the clock and to work with all Zimbabweans in dialogue for a better future.</p><p>We will continue to raise our serious concerns and push for a thorough investigation with the Government of Zimbabwe, through our Embassy in Harare and Ministerial interventions.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-05T12:21:19.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046320/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046320/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Zimbabwe: Violence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Zimbabwe following the recent violence and deaths associated with the protests in that country.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Southwark",,"The Lord Bishop of Southwark","HL13028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046321","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>We have regular discussions with the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank, UN agencies and other international partners on the economic situation in Zimbabwe and the impact on the Zimbabwean people.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-05T12:20:49.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046321/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046321/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Zimbabwe: Economic Situation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with international partners about the current economic situation in Zimbabwe and the impact of that situation on the citizens of that country.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Southwark",,"The Lord Bishop of Southwark","HL13029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046322","Department for Education","false","2019-02-05","<p>Following the Raising Participation Age legislation introduced in 2013-14 in England, young people are now required to stay in education or training until at least their 18th birthday.</p><p>The attached table shows the latest official participation figures for 16 and 17 year olds who are not in full-time education in England. Many 16 and 17 year olds are enrolled in other forms of education that are not classified as full-time. The number of 16 and 17 year olds who are not in education or training is also included and this shows those not in any education and training (those not in full or part-time education, on an apprenticeship or in employer-funded training).</p>1.0.0.20",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2019-02-05T17:08:57.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046322/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046322/answer","HL13030 table showing the number of 16 and 17 year olds not in full-time education.doc","HL13030_table_children_not_in_full_time_education","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046322/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-22","Young People: Unemployment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many young people of education age in England are not in full-time education.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL13030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046323","Department for Education","false","2019-01-30","<p>A number of types of institution can be commissioned to provide Alternative Provision (AP), including independent schools and unregistered providers. The department does not hold data on all providers, and therefore does not hold the total number of such providers.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2018 there were 352 Pupil Referral Units, AP academies, and AP free schools in England.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on AP providers can be obtained from the department’s register of schools and colleges in England ‘Get information about schools’ which can be accessed using the online tool available here: <a href="https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold information on whether pupils were previously excluded before joining their current school or provider.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL13032","2019-01-30T17:40:29.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046323/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046323/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-22","Alternative Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many alternative education providers are registered in England; and how many (1) permanently excluded, and (2) other excluded pupils are in such provision.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL13031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046324","Department for Education","false","2019-01-30","<p>A number of types of institution can be commissioned to provide Alternative Provision (AP), including independent schools and unregistered providers. The department does not hold data on all providers, and therefore does not hold the total number of such providers.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2018 there were 352 Pupil Referral Units, AP academies, and AP free schools in England.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on AP providers can be obtained from the department’s register of schools and colleges in England ‘Get information about schools’ which can be accessed using the online tool available here: <a href="https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold information on whether pupils were previously excluded before joining their current school or provider.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL13031","2019-01-30T17:40:29.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046324/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046324/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-22","Alternative Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the number of unregistered alternative education providers in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL13032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046326","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-31","<p>We are aware that the Zimbabwean government shut down the internet and blocked a number of social media sites, including Facebook, Twitter and Whatsapp from 15 January.</p><p>On 17 January, the Minister for Africa, Harriett Baldwin MP, summoned the Zimbabwean Ambassador and urged the Zimbabwean government to stop the disproportionate use of force, investigate any alleged human rights violations and restore full access to the internet. On 21 January the Foreign Secretary repeated the call in a public message to President Mnangagwa.</p><p>We welcome the 21 January ruling of the Zimbabwean High Court that overturned the government decision to shut down the internet.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-01-31T14:30:49.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046326/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046326/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Zimbabwe: Internet","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports that the government of Zimbabwe has instructed internal providers to disconnect and restrict internet access.","false","Biography information for Baroness Stroud",,"Baroness Stroud","HL13033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046327","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-31","<p>The Minister for Africa, Harriett Baldwin MP, summoned the Zimbabwean Ambassador on 17 January to express our concern at the ongoing situation in Zimbabwe. Minister Baldwin urged Zimbabwe to stop disproportionate use of force by the security forces and investigate any cases of alleged human rights abuses. On 21 January the Foreign Secretary, in a public message to President Mnangagwa, urged him not to turn back the clock and to work with all Zimbabweans in dialogue for a better future.</p><p>We will continue to raise our serious concerns, and push for a thorough investigation, with the Government of Zimbabwe through our Embassy in Harare and Ministerial interventions.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-01-31T14:31:35.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046327/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046327/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Zimbabwe following reports of recent violence; and what plans they have for continued engagement with that government on that issue.","false","Biography information for Baroness Stroud",,"Baroness Stroud","HL13034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046328","Treasury","false","2019-02-04","<p>The UK has established strong, independent economic regulators that protect the interests of consumers and encourage high levels of investment.</p><p> </p><p>The economic regulators – Ofgem, Ofwat, Ofcom, and the Civil Aviation Authority – ensure that regulated companies deliver good value for money, and that investors get a fair return on their investment.</p><p> </p><p>This system continues to deliver strong levels of investment. For instance, in the water sector, over the next price control period companies have proposed investing £50 billion from 2020-2025, a 13% increase from the previous control period. In 2017, the inward stock of FDI in the UK was the highest in Europe and the third highest in the world.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2019-02-04T14:19:08.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046328/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046328/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-22","Infrastructure: Capital Investment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports that infrastructure investors may be withholding investment in the UK due to concerns about the current regulatory climate.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL13035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046329","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-05","<p>The Government's top priority is to conclude a withdrawal agreement. To help ensure that passengers are well informed about the requirements which will apply in a no deal scenario, we are working with ferry and port operators and directly with passengers through technical notices and other communications. This includes issues such as passports and the carriage of pets.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is also closely involved with Kent delivery partners to help smooth passenger traffic flows, avoid conflicts with HGV flows so far as possible, and to make welfare provisions for tourists and other motorists.</p><p> </p><p>No significant disruption is expected for ferry passengers at other ports.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2019-02-05T16:19:44.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046329/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046329/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-01-22","Channel Ferries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to work with the shipping industry to help minimise disruption for ferry passengers in the event of a no-deal Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL13036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046330","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-05","<p>UK border controls will prioritise freight flow, partly by taking newly-required checks away from the frontier as far as possible.</p><p> </p><p>Disruption is, however, possible in a no-deal scenario if third-country controls applied at EU ports, particularly on the short Strait, are onerous. The reasonable worst case scenario being used as a planning assumption is one in which flow through the short Channel crossings (both imports and exports) is reduced very significantly for up to 6 months<em>; </em>and where a substantial percentage of agrifood products would have to be routed away from these locations.</p><p> </p><p>The contracts we have agreed with ferry companies DFDS, Brittany Ferries and Seaborne Freight will contribute to ensuring smooth trade operations by enhancing ro-ro capacity available on Channel and North Sea crossings.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2019-02-05T16:38:01.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046330/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046330/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-01-22","Channel Ferries: Freight","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of whether there will be severe disruption of freight traffic in a no-deal Brexit scenario; and what plans, if any, they have to ensure smooth trade operations between the UK and France after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL13037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046331","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-05","<p>Australia has welcomed UK interest in potential accession to CPTPP, with the Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison stating in October 2018 that “the British would be pushing on an open door with us on this issue&quot;. The UK and Australia already have a strong and historic trading relationship and both countries are proponents of trade liberalisation and the rules based international system. We share an ambition to enhance this trading relationship after we leave the EU, both bilaterally through a new Free Trade Agreement and through potential accession to CPTPP.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2019-02-05T12:42:11.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046331/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046331/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-22","Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the government of Australia’s position on the UK joining the Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL13038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046332","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-02-04","<p>Her Majesty's Government works closely with the Israeli Defence Force (IDF) in order to counter the destabilising regional activity of Iran and Hezbollah, and to conduct operations against Daesh. The IDF also provides crucial access and overflight for the RAF to be able to conduct air operations in support of Op SHADER. Accordingly, in support of this important defence relationship, the RAF invited the Israeli Air Force to join Exercise COBRA WARRIOR, alongside RAF, German, and Italian Air Force Units.</p><p> </p><p>The Exercise enables participating Air Forces to learn mutual lessons from operating together; just as the RAF does on exercise with many other Air Forces. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) has a contract with Elbit Systems UK for the MORPHEUS Battlefield Management Application. Under the contract Elbit Systems UK will provide the British Army with an operationally proven battle management application for both headquarters and tactical units. As with all MOD contractors, we assess the legal and financial status of a company before placing a contract, and take into account any other factors which may impact on delivery of the requirements.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2019-02-04T15:18:02.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046332/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046332/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-01-22","Israel: Joint Exercises","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government why they have invited the Israeli Air Force to join the Royal Air Force in Exercise Cobra Warrior in September 2019; and what consideration they gave, when awarding a contract to Elbit Systems UK, of the use of that company by the government of Israel.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL13039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046333","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-04","<p>We regularly make clear our serious concerns about the situation in East Jerusalem to the Israeli authorities and the Municipality of Jerusalem. We remain deeply concerned about restrictions on freedom of movement to and from East Jerusalem.</p><p>​</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-04T17:16:35.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046333/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046333/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Jerusalem: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding the status of Palestinians in East Jerusalem who have been denied full Israeli citizenship and cannot travel abroad.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL13040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046334","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>We regularly raise our grave concerns on this issue with the Government of Israel and urge it to freeze its policy of settlement expansion. The UK’s position on settlements is clear. They are illegal under international law, present an obstacle to peace, and threaten the physical viability of a two-state solution. Most recently the Minister for the Middle East released a statement on 27 December urging Israel to cease settlement activity.​</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-05T12:24:40.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046334/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046334/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Israeli Settlements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel about the seizure of land close to Ramallah to build Jewish settlements.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL13041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046335","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>We are concerned by recent incursions by Israeli forces into Area A of the West Bank. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv raised this with the Israeli authorities on 15 January.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-05T12:24:03.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046335/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046335/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel about the number of raids by Israel on Area A of the West Bank and the city of Ramallah.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL13042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046337","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-04","<p>We have not recently raised this issue with the Israeli authorities.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-04T17:16:48.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046337/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046337/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel about (1) the number of, and (2) the level of fines imposed on Palestinians.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL13043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046338","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-05","<p>We have not made an assessment of this issue. We encourage Israel and the Palestinians to do all they can to work together to avoid tensions and continue to uphold the status quo at the holy sites in Jerusalem.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-05T12:23:46.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046338/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046338/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-22","Jerusalem: Road Traffic Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports of proposals that parts of the old city wall of Jerusalem should be demolished for traffic calming measures; and what representations they have made to the government of Israel about such proposals.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL13044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046339","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-01-31","<p>Through our Nuclear Sector deal, Government continue to explore whether advanced nuclear technologies, such as small modular reactors, could be an important source of low carbon energy in the future.</p><p>The deal also highlights a new framework designed to aid the development of advanced nuclear technologies. The framework includes consideration of financing, siting and international collaboration as well as building regulatory readiness for advanced reactors.</p><p>The Government has committed up to £12m to build the regulatory capability and capacity of the nuclear regulators, the Office for Nuclear Regulation and the Environment Agency, to develop their ability to take future licensing decisions on small and advanced reactor designs.</p><p>We also committed, with the regulators, to modernise and open Generic Design Assessment (GDA) for small reactors. This regulatory process assesses the safety, security and environmental aspects of a new nuclear reactor design. In December 2018, Expressions of Interest were invited for the GDA process for small and advanced modular reactors. We have received 5 so far for GDAs commencing between 2019 and 2023. We will open a process for formal applications soon.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2019-01-31T16:43:58.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046339/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046339/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-01-22","Nuclear Reactors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they are having with Rolls-Royce about small modular reactors (SMRs); and what progress the Office for Nuclear Regulation has made in approving those SMRs for operation.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL13045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046803","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-30","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply and their response will be placed in the Library.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2019-01-30T13:09:15.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046803/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046803/answer","PQ 211822 (1).pdf","UKSA Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1046803/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-01-22","Knowledge Economy: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of the work force in each (a) region and (b) local authority area is employed in the knowledge economy.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","211822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1041772","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-01-21","<p>Solar projects recorded on the Renewable Energy Planning Database (REPD) in each quarter since 2014 are in the following table. Please note that the management of the REPD changed in October 2014 and the historical data for 2013 and 2014 Q1 is not available.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the new contract for administering the REPD at the start of Q4 2014, the data parameters were changed to increase the minimum installed capacity from 0.001MW to 1MW. Therefore, the data shown from Q4 2014 onwards includes only those schemes with an installed capacity 1MW or above until Q4 2018 when projects over 150kW started to be included.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-01-21T18:06:15.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1041772/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1041772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1041772/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-01-21","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many solar-based projects were on the Renewal Energy Planning Database in each quarter of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","208941"
